<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n20217a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n20" href="#n20217a">N20 (VI.B.13)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n20all.htm#n20217a"> 217(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 3 tenors / When wind blows / Miller &amp; His Men / Bishop</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Three tenor voices in one family are rarely met with, and when the brothers sang together &hellip; they may have joined in Bishop&apos;s round &ldquo;When the wind blows,&rdquo; from <cite>The Miller and his Men</cite> &mdash; one of the few concerted pieces written for three tenors. If so, the effect of the haunting melody repeated and harmonised in tones so akin to one another must have been a musical treat almost unique. <small> Charles E. Pearce, <a name="CEPS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CEPS"><cite title="source">Sims Reeves: Fifty Years of Music in England</cite></a> (Jun 1924) 23</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
